<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="81.[151,1436,350,1095]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,350,375]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body pentagonal (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[560,668,350,375]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="87.[151,250,1896,1918]" captionTargetBox="[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@87.[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="FIGURE 31. Sphaeriodiscus biomaglo n. sp. Holotype IE-2013-17197. R=3.3, r=2.2 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. B. Closeup showing abactinal plates and granulation. Scale bar=0.5 cm. C. Arm tip and superomarginal plate surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Actinal plate surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Closeup of furrow and adambulacral spination. Scale bar=0.3 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615988/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 31A</figureCitation>
). Abactinal plates weakly tabulate, covered by evenly distributed granules (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[321,428,386,411]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="87.[151,250,1896,1918]" captionTargetBox="[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@87.[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="FIGURE 31. Sphaeriodiscus biomaglo n. sp. Holotype IE-2013-17197. R=3.3, r=2.2 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. B. Closeup showing abactinal plates and granulation. Scale bar=0.5 cm. C. Arm tip and superomarginal plate surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Actinal plate surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Closeup of furrow and adambulacral spination. Scale bar=0.3 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615988/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 31B</figureCitation>
). Marginal plates few, tumid with swollen or enlarged penultimates (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[1316,1423,386,411]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="87.[151,250,1896,1918]" captionTargetBox="[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetId="figure@87.[204,1394,195,1867]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="FIGURE 31. Sphaeriodiscus biomaglo n. sp. Holotype IE-2013-17197. R=3.3, r=2.2 cm. A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. B. Closeup showing abactinal plates and granulation. Scale bar=0.5 cm. C. Arm tip and superomarginal plate surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm. D. Actinal plate surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Closeup of furrow and adambulacral spination. Scale bar=0.3 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2615988/files/figure.png" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Fig. 31C</figureCitation>
). Pedicellariae spatulate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="81.[151,1436,350,1095]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,458,483]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1910" box="[352,523,458,483]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,523,458,483]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
together with 
<emphasis box="[714,815,458,483]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Peltaster</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[889,1025,459,482]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<taxonomicName box="[889,1021,459,482]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Ceramaster</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which all share similar defining characters, including a pentagonal body shape, relatively few marginal plates, shallow to well-developed abactinal plates, granule-covered, either partially or completely, marginal plates with bald region on the superomarginal surface, and variably granule to spinelet covered abactinal and actinal surfaces. Several characters present among species within these genera overlap or else show poor correspondence with taxonomic concept boundaries.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="81.[151,1436,350,1095]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
Seven species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1910" box="[404,575,638,663]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[404,575,638,663]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently recognized (Mah, 2018), including five Pacific species, one Atlantic species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perrier" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[344,617,674,699]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="bourgeti">
<emphasis box="[344,617,674,699]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus bourgeti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. M. Clark" authorityYear="1976" box="[679,959,674,699]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis box="[679,959,674,699]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the southern Indian Ocean, included herein. 
<bibRefCitation author="Fisher, W. K." box="[248,413,710,735]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="987 - 1130" refId="ref70129" refString="Fisher, W. K. (1906) The starfishes of the Hawaiian islands. Bulletin of the United States Fish Commission, 23, 987 - 1130." type="journal article" year="1906">Fisher (1906)</bibRefCitation>
established 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1910" box="[579,750,710,735]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[579,750,710,735]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on an enlarged “ultimate or ante-penultimate” superomarginal plate. 
<collectingRegion box="[402,444,747,770]" country="Maldives" name="Uthuru" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Not</collectingRegion>
all of these species fall within the constraints of the original genus definition as clearly as the 
<typeStatus box="[232,280,783,807]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fisher" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[392,712,782,807]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ammophilus">
<emphasis box="[392,712,782,807]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus ammophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Enlarged near-terminal superomarginals are present in many species of each genus and in some specimens, enlarged plates are variably, absent or weakly developed. There has, for example, been some question as to the placement of 
<emphasis box="[811,1019,854,879]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Peltaster placenta</emphasis>
in 
<emphasis box="[1060,1161,854,879]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Peltaster</emphasis>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1910" box="[1205,1376,854,879]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1205,1376,854,879]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tortonese, E. &amp; Clark, A. M." box="[151,444,890,915]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="347 - 352" refId="ref74717" refString="Tortonese, E. &amp; Clark, A. M. (1956) On the generic position of the asteroid Goniodiscus placenta Muller &amp; Troschel. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 12, 9, 347 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222935608655821" type="journal article" year="1956">Tortonese and Clark 1956</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tortonese, E." box="[455,633,891,915]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="99 - 112" refId="ref74675" refString="Tortonese, E. (1984) Notes on the Mediterranean sea-star Peltaster placenta (M. Tr.) (Echinodermata, Asteroidea). Bollettino del Museo civico di storia naturale di Ferona, 11, 99 - 112." type="journal article" year="1984">Tortonese 1984</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequent authors, such as 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G." box="[974,1371,890,915]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 270" refId="ref69285" refString="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G. (2001) The Marine Fauna of New Zealand: Echinodermata: Asteroidea (sea-stars), Order Valvatida. NIWA Biodiversity Memoir, 117, 1 - 270." type="journal article" year="2001">H.E.S. Clark and McKnight (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, have liberally applied the enlarged ultimate/antepenultimate marginal plate criterion and differing definitions of “enlarged” have qualified different species as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1910" box="[666,837,962,987]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[666,837,962,987]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
versus 
<emphasis box="[923,1028,962,987]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Peltaster.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="81.[151,1436,350,1095]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,454,998,1023]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Type Specimen Note.</emphasis>
Perrier’s original type series of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Perrier" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[827,1102,998,1023]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Sphaeriodiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="bourgeti">
<emphasis box="[827,1102,998,1023]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Sphaeriodiscus bourgeti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in the 
<mcCollectionCode box="[1213,1298,999,1022]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">MNHN</mcCollectionCode>
collections, rendering 
<bibRefCitation author="Halpern, J. A." box="[273,472,1034,1059]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="193 - 286" refId="ref70647" refString="Halpern, J. A. (1970) Goniasteridae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) of the Straits of Florida. Bulletin of Marine Science, 20 (1), 193 - 286." type="journal article" year="1970">Halpern’s (1970)</bibRefCitation>
conclusion that the 
<mcCollectionCode box="[731,792,1035,1059]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33791" name="Museum of Comparative Zoology" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="Museum">MCZ</mcCollectionCode>
specimens were the only extant types incorrect and designation of the specimens as 
<typeStatus box="[512,615,1070,1095]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">lectotype</typeStatus>
and paralectoype inappropriate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
